```bash
#!/bin/bash

# Create an example .env file with default values
echo "Creating .example.env file..."

cat > .example.env <<EOF
# Example environment variables
DB_HOST=localhost
DB_PORT=5432
DB_NAME=mydatabase
DB_USER=myuser
DB_PASSWORD=mypassword
EOF

if [ $? -eq 0 ]; then
  echo ".example.env file created successfully."
else
  echo "Failed to create .example.env file."
fi
```

This script creates a `.example.env` file with default environment variable values. The `cat > .example.env` command redirects the output of the `EOF` block to the new file, creating it if it doesn't exist. If the creation is successful, the pipeline status will be "success" and no risks or action items will be reported.
